\details{
There’s a few different times that we want to alter the tuning parameter
information:
\itemize{
\item To change the default for a specific model and engine (e.g. boosted
trees often use higher \code{learn_rate} values than other models).
\item To add possible engine arguments.
}

\code{add_engine_parameters()} adds engine-specific tunable parameters to a
base result. If any base parameters have the same name as engine
parameters, the engine versions replace them.

\code{apply_tunable_spec()} is a higher-level function that applies a
specification list to modify tunable parameters. It supports three
patterns:
\itemize{
\item Adding parameters,
\item Updating existing parameters, or
\item Completely replacing the parameter value’s information.
}

Examples are below.
\subsection{Structure of the \code{call_info}}{

\code{call_info} is just a list that is used to create a new parameter
object. For example:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{penalty_info <- list(pkg = "dials", fun = "penalty")

# How it is used internally: 
rlang::call2(.ns = penalty_info$pkg,  penalty_info$fun)
#> dials::penalty()
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

The list names should match parameter names, and values should be lists
with \code{pkg}, \code{fun}, and optionally \code{range} or \code{values}. Use this to
change the function or range for existing parameters.

\strong{Note}: for engines defined in and its extensions, parameter ranges
should be set when the argument is registered via \code{set_model_arg()}. The
updates mechanism is a another way of doing the same thing if the
preferred method cannot be used.
}

\subsection{Examples}{

Let’s say that you are writing a parsnip extension package for your
fancy new \emph{GlamNet} model (a fabulous regularized linear regression
technique). Your package has registration code that looks like:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{set_model_engine("linear_reg", "regression", "GlamNet")
set_dependency("linear_reg", "GlamNet", "GlamNet", mode = "regression")

set_fit(
  model = "linear_reg",
  eng = "GlamNet",
  mode = "regression",
  value = list(
    interface = "matrix",
    protect = c("x", "y", "weights"),
    func = c(pkg = "GlamNet", fun = "GlamNet")
  )
)

set_encoding(
  model = "linear_reg",
  eng = "GlamNet",
  mode = "regression",
  options = list(
    predictor_indicators = "traditional",
    compute_intercept = TRUE,
    remove_intercept = TRUE,
    allow_sparse_x = TRUE
  )
)

set_model_arg(
  model = "linear_reg",
  eng = "GlamNet",
  parsnip = "penalty",
  original = "lambda",
  func = list(pkg = "dials", fun = "penalty"),
  has_submodel = TRUE
)

set_model_arg(
  model = "linear_reg",
  eng = "GlamNet",
  parsnip = "mixture",
  original = "alpha",
  func = list(pkg = "dials", fun = "mixture"),
  has_submodel = FALSE
)

# etc etc
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

However, you want to do two things:
\itemize{
\item Update the main argument \code{mixture} to have a range of \link[=0.9, 1]{0.9, 1}.
\item Tell tidymodels about the engine argument \code{glitter_amount} in case
someone wants to tune it.
}

For the first issue, you can modify the registration code to be

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{set_model_arg(
  model = "linear_reg",
  eng = "GlamNet",
  parsnip = "mixture",
  original = "alpha",
  func = list(pkg = "dials", fun = "mixture", range = c(0.9, 1.0)),
  has_submodel = FALSE
)
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

This is the \emph{preferred} method but another will be shown below.

For the second issue related to engine arguments, you make a tibble of
information about how to call a parameter function for \code{glitter_amount}:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{glam_engine_params <- tibble::tibble(
  name = "glitter_amount",
  # The dials parameter can be in your extension package or in dials
  call_info = list(list(pkg = "GlamNet", fun = "glitter_amount")),
  source = "model_spec",
  component = "linear_reg",
  component_id = "engine"
)
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

Let’s \emph{pretend} that the \code{GlamNet} model spec is the same as what we
would get from \code{glmnet}:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{glam_spec <- linear_reg() |> set_engine("glmnet")
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

If we want to append the engine parameter information to what we would
get from \code{tunable()}, we use

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{add_engine_parameters(tunable(glam_spec), glam_engine_params)
#> # A tibble: 3 x 5
#>   name           call_info        source     component  component_id
#>   <chr>          <list>           <chr>      <chr>      <chr>       
